Introduction

Required Libraries

In order to examine this dataset, the following libraries are required and loaded. This dataset is not available in base-R; therefore, we need to read the dataset first as follows:

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(corrplot) #For correlation plot
library(knitr)
#Prepare data
survey <- read.csv("~responses.csv", sep = ",") %>%
  select(History:Pets) %>%
  filter(complete.cases(.)) %>%
  tbl_df()
#Prepare PCA data
survey <- survey[,sapply(survey,class)=="integer"]

Overview of Dataset

  • In 2013, students of the Statistics class at FSEV UK were asked to invite their friends to participate in this survey.
  • All participants were of Slovakian nationality, aged between 15-30.
  • The data file consists of 886 rows and 32 columns.
  • All columns are related with hobbies and interests.
  • â1â is NOT interested and â5â is VERY interested.

  • According to correlation plot, Biology is highly correlated with Chemistry and Medicine.
  • Politics is positive correlated with Law.
  • Theatre is positive correlated with Reading and Art-exhibitions.
  • Reading is negative correlated with Cars.

Objectives

  • Exploring the dataset survey
  • Examining categories that correlate with each other
  • By implementing Principal Components Analysis, examining the proportion of variances and reducing the number of explanatory variables
  • By applying Multidimensional Scaling, examining the relationship of âHobby and Interestsâ in a 2 dimensional environment
  • Clustering them with K-Means Methods and Hierarchical Clustering to investigate the clusters
  • By building a simple linear model, examining the relationship of âBiologyâ with others

Principal Components Analysis (PCA)

## Pets
  • PCA is a method to reduce the number of explanatory variables. The resulting principle components (PCs) are actually linear transformations of our explanatory variables.
  • For example, the second PC considers Reading, Shopping and Theatre as negative effects, and Politics, Mathematics, Physics, Internet, PC, Economy-Management, Geography, Law, Cars, Passive-sports, Active-sports, Science-and-Technology, and Adrenaline-sports as a positive effect.
ggplot(data = data.frame(PC = 1:length(survey_pca_result$sdev), var_exp = cumsum(survey_pca_result$sdev^2 / sum(survey_pca_result$sdev^2))), aes(x = PC, y = var_exp)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, color = "black") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.9, color = "blue2") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 24, color = "blue2") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.8, color = "green2") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 18, color = "green2") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent,breaks=seq(0,1,length.out=11)) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0,32,by=2)) +
  labs(title = "Trade-off Graph between Explanatory Power and number of Explanatory Variables", y = "Cumulative Explained Variance in %")

  • As seen from the graph, the first 24 PCs are responsible for 90% (blue hline) of the variation.
  • Resulting PCA analysis helps us to maintain 80% (green hline) of the variance with just 18 (out of 32) of the survey questions.
  • Here we analyzed the survey results. Therefore, it will be more accurate to apply multidimensional scaling and/or hierarchical clustering to classify hobbies and interests.
  • If there was an extra column in our dataset that concerns people participating in the survey (such as exam result), we could train and test our data with using the first 18 PCs (rather than 32).

Multidimensional Scaling (MDS)

  • Multidimensional scaling is a means of visualizing the level of similarity of individual cases of a dataset. MDS refers to a set of related ordination techniques used in information visualization, in particular to display the information contained in a distance matrix.
  • We would like to see the how respondents preferences correlation among different âhobby and interestsâ. We are going to use the correlation matrix as a similarity measure.
#Correlation is a similarity measure between -1 and 1
#Get the negative of it as a distance measure and add 1 to make sure distances start from 0
survey_dist <- 1 - cor(survey)

#Apply MDS into 2 dimensional scale
survey_mds <- cmdscale(survey_dist, k=2)

#Provide column names
colnames(survey_mds) <- c("x","y")

print(survey_mds)

K-Means

  • K-Means is one of the most popular clustering algoritms.
  • It is an unsupervised method. We donât need a response variable or pre-labeled data.
  • In the classical form, given a number of (say, k) clusters, the algorithm adds nodes to the clusters to minimize the variance within cluster (i.e.Â squared distance from the cluster center to the nodes).
  • Letâs apply K-Means to the Young People Survey MDS output.

Determining the Number of Cluster (k)

set.seed(100)
sum_of_squares <- c()
for(i in 2:15){ 
  fit <- kmeans(survey_mds, centers = i)
  sum_of_squares[i] <- 100 * round(1-(fit$tot.withinss/fit$totss),digits = 3)
}
plot(x=1:15, y=sum_of_squares, xlab = "Number of clusters", ylab = "Between_SS / Total_SS")
lines(1:15, sum_of_squares)
abline(h=80)
abline(h=90)
abline(v=6)

  • The total within-cluster sum of square measures the compactness (i.e goodness) of the clustering and we want it to be as small as possible.
  • It would be reasonable to choose 6 clusters since the rate of increase started to decrease after that point.

K-Means using Multidimensional Scaling Data

#Set the seed since K-Means algorithm uses a search based method
set.seed(100)

#Apply K-Means

#Get the clusters

Hierarchical Clustering

  • In Hierarchical Clustering, there are clusters within larger clusters, resulting in a tree like structure.
  • There are also two types of hierarchical clustering methods, divisive (âtop-downâ) or agglomerative (âbottom-upâ).
  • The former starts with all the nodes in a cluster and splits the clusters on the way down and the latter starts merging nodes up to a single cluster.
  • Weâll apply agglomerative clusters as below;

Single Link Clustering

  • Single link (or MIN) is known to minimize the closest dissimilarity between the nodes in pairwise clusters.
### Single link (MIN) method
survey_hc_min <- hclust(as.dist(survey_dist), method="single")
plot(survey_hc_min, hang=-1)

  • Using this method, it is not clear from where to cluster. Since the variance change is quite low between the number of clustering, we can determine higher k number.
  • As expected, Biology and Medicine are in the same sub-cluster, while Chemistry joins them in one top cluster. In another top cluster, it is seen that it is related to those to the right of the graph.
  • Likewise, Politics and Law merge with History in a higher cluster. Then, Economy-Management is included in the upper cluster. Geography is included in another top cluster.
  • Celebrities and Shopping, Politics and Law, Theater and Art-Exhibitions, Active-sports and Adrenaline-sports, Internet and PC are located in the same sub-cluster.
  • Pets doesnât create clusters with any variables. In any case, Pets will act independently of other variables.

Complete Link Clustering

  • Complete link (or MAX) is the opposite, it wants to minimize the largest dissimilarity.
### Complete link (MAX) method
survey_hc_max <- hclust(as.dist(survey_dist), method="complete")
plot(survey_hc_max, hang=-1)

  • The variance within the group increases most when moving from number of 3 clusters to 2 clusters. For this case, it would be logical to divide it into 3 clusters.
  • This time, we see Pets is paired with Celebrities and Shopping.
  • On the right, the sport groups and some activities are paired together.
  • On the left, we see that the science branches and the technological categories match.
  • In the middle, the terms related with language, culture, lessons, habits and some daily activities are paired together.

Average Link Clustering

  • Average method aims to minimize the average distance between nodes in each cluster.
### Average method
survey_hc_avg <- hclust(as.dist(survey_dist), method="average")
plot(survey_hc_avg, hang=-1)

  • We got a result similar to the previous method.
  • Here, we can keep the number k slightly higher (like 6-7).
  • Thus, we can see the cluster distinctions more clearly and easily name the clusters.

Supervised Learning

Linear Regression

#Run a simple linear regression
ggplot(data=survey) + 
  geom_jitter(aes(x=Biology, y=Medicine, color=Biology)) + 
  geom_smooth(method='lm',aes(x=Biology,y=Medicine),se=FALSE)

  • We clearly see a positive trend between Biology and Medicine.
  • At points where Biology is low by surveyors, Medicine also scored low. This statement is also valid in other points. Now, we will apply a linear model and see the significance level.

Linear Model: Biology ~ Medicine
